d and Pas-de-Calais): ethnic name from a derivative of Old French <i>teis</i> ‘German, Flemish’, from ancient Germanic <i>theod</i> ‘people’. Compare   Teson   and   Tesson  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Theissen   or   Theisen  . Compare   Tyson  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roche","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de la Roche Tesson was born about 1110, in Cesny-Bois-Halbout, Calvados, Normandy, France, her father, Robert III De La Roche Tesson, was 22 and her mother, Adélicie DE FRANCE, was 17. She had at least 1 son with Guillaume de La Lande-Patry IV. She died in 1160, in La Lande-